nel Project -- tLa Vérité -- tCanadian Centre for Child Protection -- tResidential School in City’s Backyard -- tReunion, Remembrance, and Reclamation -- tReunion and Remembrance: Gathering Knowledge -- tThe Legacy of Reunion, Remembrance, and Reclamation -- tAcknowledgements -- tAppendix: Assiniboia Indian Residential School Timeline -- tNotes -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Assiniboia school is unique within Canada’s Indian Residential School system. It was the first residential high school in Manitoba and one of the only residential schools in Canada to be located in a large urban setting. Operating between 1958 and 1973 in a period when the residential school system was in decline, it produced several future leaders, artists, educators, knowledge keepers, and other notable figures. It was in many ways an experiment within the broader destructive framework of Canadian residential schools. Stitching together memories of arrival at, day-to-day life within, and departure from the school with a socio-historical reconstruction of the school and its position in both Winnipeg and the larger residential school system, Did You See Us? offers a glimpse of Assiniboia that is not available in the archival records. It connects readers with a specific residential school and illustrates that residential schools were often complex spaces where forced assimilation and Indigenous resilience co-existed. These recollections of Assiniboia at times diverge, but together exhibit Survivor resilience and the strength of the relationships that bond them to this day. The volume captures the troubled history of residential schools. At the same time, it invites the reader to join in a reunion of sorts, entered into through memories and images of students, staff, and neighbours. It is a gathering of diverse knowledges juxtaposed to communicate the complexity of the residential school experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzManitobazWinnipegxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndigenous peopleszManitobavBiography. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aCrate, Dorothy-Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEll, Sister Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Morgan Sizeland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontaine, Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlennon, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, Hubert (Gilbert), econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolbrow, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorton, Mabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMainville, Valerie T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarchildon, Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Lianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelson, Charlie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerreault, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotosky, Aila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobson, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Betty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/